WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.200
Black Cat Presents, I Want to Be You by Andrea M. Hutchinson Copyright Black Cat Publishing

00:30.200 --> 00:33.200
Teammates

00:33.200 --> 00:37.200
Hurry up girls, the match starts in 10 minutes.

00:37.200 --> 00:40.200
Says Miss Stevens the PE teacher.

00:40.200 --> 00:44.200
And remember, what are we going to do?

00:44.200 --> 00:45.200
Win!

00:45.200 --> 00:47.200
Everyone shouts.

00:47.200 --> 00:52.200
Miss Stevens leaves the changing rooms and Rosie starts putting on makeup.

00:52.200 --> 00:55.200
Don't look at me like that's Holly.

00:55.200 --> 00:56.200
Says Rosie.

00:56.200 --> 00:58.200
You know it's...

00:58.200 --> 01:00.200
I start to say.

01:00.200 --> 01:03.200
Against school rules to wear makeup.

01:03.200 --> 01:07.200
She says in a silly voice and everyone laughs.

01:07.200 --> 01:10.200
You're so boring Holly.

01:10.200 --> 01:12.200
Says Jane, Rosie's best friend.

01:12.200 --> 01:15.200
There's a photographer from the local newspaper.

01:15.200 --> 01:17.200
I need to look my best.

01:17.200 --> 01:19.200
Says Rosie.

01:19.200 --> 01:24.200
Rosie is the team captain, our best player and my cousin.

01:24.200 --> 01:27.200
We were even born on the same day.

01:27.200 --> 01:29.200
But we aren't similar at all.

01:29.200 --> 01:31.200
Rosie likes sport.

01:31.200 --> 01:33.200
I like painting.

01:33.200 --> 01:36.200
I love chocolate and baking cakes.

01:36.200 --> 01:39.200
Rosie is always on a diet.

01:39.200 --> 01:44.200
This week, she's only eating things that begin with the letter P.

01:44.200 --> 01:48.200
Pineapple, peppers and peas.

01:48.200 --> 01:56.200
I like pineapples, but every day, for seven days, she's crazy.

01:56.200 --> 01:58.200
Her family is rich.

01:58.200 --> 02:00.200
Mine is not.

02:00.200 --> 02:05.200
We're not poor, but Rosie's mum and dad, Art Lily and Uncle Pete,

02:05.200 --> 02:08.200
have lots and lots of money.

02:08.200 --> 02:11.200
They go on holiday in the Seychelles.

02:11.200 --> 02:15.200
We go on holiday in a caravan in Scotland.

02:15.200 --> 02:17.200
They moved house last month.

02:17.200 --> 02:23.200
Art Lily told mum it was because they needed an extra room for their gym and sauna.

02:23.200 --> 02:26.200
We don't really see them very often.

02:26.200 --> 02:30.200
To be honest, we really couldn't be more different if we tried.

02:30.200 --> 02:35.200
The only thing Rosie and I both have is blonde hair.

02:35.200 --> 02:40.200
Rosie's is long and straight, and it always looks perfect.

02:40.200 --> 02:46.200
Mine is short and curly, and I always look like a clown.

02:46.200 --> 02:47.200
Ready!

02:47.200 --> 02:50.200
Rosie asked the team with a nervous smile.

02:50.200 --> 02:53.200
Yes, the let's go!

02:53.200 --> 02:56.200
The team followed her to the gym.

02:56.200 --> 03:00.200
As usual, I'm the last one to leave the changing rooms.

03:00.200 --> 03:05.200
I sit down with the other reserves and cross my fingers.

03:05.200 --> 03:10.200
Please, I hope they don't need me.

03:10.200 --> 03:12.200
I hate basketball.

03:12.200 --> 03:19.200
I hate science, Sudoku and supermodels, but I hate basketball most.

03:20.200 --> 03:23.200
The game starts well.

03:23.200 --> 03:26.200
Rosie scores twice in five minutes.

03:26.200 --> 03:31.200
Every time she scores, she smiles at the photographer.

03:31.200 --> 03:35.200
Across the gym, Ben is sitting with his friends.

03:35.200 --> 03:40.200
I think Ben is gorgeous, but he doesn't know I exist.

03:40.200 --> 03:44.200
No boy like Ben ever looks at a girl like me.

03:44.200 --> 03:46.200
I look at the clock.

03:46.200 --> 03:52.200
210, 209, 08, 07.

03:52.200 --> 03:53.200
Great!

03:53.200 --> 03:57.200
Only two more minutes before the game is over.

03:57.200 --> 04:00.200
The score is 22-23.

04:00.200 --> 04:03.200
The other team is winning, but Rosie has the ball.

04:03.200 --> 04:07.200
She runs past one player and then another.

04:07.200 --> 04:11.200
As she gets closer to the basket, everyone stands up and shouts,

04:11.200 --> 04:15.200
Rosie, Rosie, Rosie.

04:15.200 --> 04:19.200
Just as I start to relax and think that I won't have to play,

04:19.200 --> 04:25.200
a player from the other team runs into Rosie and she falls to the floor.

04:25.200 --> 04:27.200
Rosie, are you okay?

04:27.200 --> 04:29.200
I run to her.

04:29.200 --> 04:31.200
My foot.

04:31.200 --> 04:34.200
It hurts.

04:34.200 --> 04:36.200
Is she going to be okay?

04:36.200 --> 04:38.200
I ask Miss Stevens.

04:38.200 --> 04:40.200
But she doesn't answer.

04:40.200 --> 04:42.200
She looks very worried.

04:42.200 --> 04:44.200
It's okay, Rosie.

04:44.200 --> 04:47.200
I say, helping her to stand up.

04:47.200 --> 04:49.200
I look after you.

04:49.200 --> 04:51.200
Holly!

04:51.200 --> 04:54.200
Miss Stevens shouts, where are you going?

04:54.200 --> 04:57.200
With my cousin to the nurse, of course.

04:57.200 --> 05:00.200
You're a reserve. The team needs you.

05:00.200 --> 05:02.200
Get on the court.

05:02.200 --> 05:05.200
But can't you choose someone else?

05:05.200 --> 05:07.200
No.

05:07.200 --> 05:08.200
It's okay.

05:08.200 --> 05:10.200
Says Rosie.

05:10.200 --> 05:11.200
Go on.

05:11.200 --> 05:13.200
We've got to win this match, Holly.

05:13.200 --> 05:15.200
I'll be okay.

05:15.200 --> 05:19.200
I don't want to, but I walk back onto the court.

05:19.200 --> 05:21.200
The referee gives me the ball.

05:21.200 --> 05:24.200
Why are you giving me the ball? I ask.

05:24.200 --> 05:26.200
Wake up, Holly!

05:26.200 --> 05:28.200
Shouts, Miss Stevens.

05:28.200 --> 05:30.200
You've got to take the penalty.

05:30.200 --> 05:31.200
But...

05:31.200 --> 05:33.200
Come on, Holly!

05:33.200 --> 05:35.200
You can do it!

05:35.200 --> 05:37.200
Shouts the team.

05:37.200 --> 05:40.200
The basket's only four meters away.

05:40.200 --> 05:43.200
It can't be difficult, can it?

05:43.200 --> 05:44.200
I aim.

05:44.200 --> 05:46.200
Close my eyes.

05:46.200 --> 05:48.200
Open them again.

05:48.200 --> 05:50.200
Take a deep breath.

05:50.200 --> 05:52.200
And shoot.

05:52.200 --> 05:58.200
Everyone watches in silence as the ball bounces first on the backboard,

05:58.200 --> 06:01.200
then on the ring, and then...

06:01.200 --> 06:04.200
No!

06:04.200 --> 06:07.200
Everyone says at the same time,

06:07.200 --> 06:11.200
the ball misses the basket and falls to the ground.

06:11.200 --> 06:14.200
The final whistle goes.

06:14.200 --> 06:16.200
Game over.

06:16.200 --> 06:18.200
The other team jump up.

06:18.200 --> 06:22.200
They lift the winner's trophy and the supporters cheer.

06:22.200 --> 06:26.200
They look so happy when they smile for the newspaper photo.

06:26.200 --> 06:28.200
Sorry, Jane.

06:28.200 --> 06:29.200
Susan.

06:29.200 --> 06:31.200
I say to my teammates.

06:31.200 --> 06:33.200
But they turn away.

06:33.200 --> 06:36.200
Even Miss Stevens looks angry with me.

06:36.200 --> 06:40.200
The team walk back to the changing rooms in silence,

06:40.200 --> 06:43.200
and I am left alone.

06:46.200 --> 06:48.200
Chapter two.

06:48.200 --> 06:51.200
I hate my life.

06:51.200 --> 06:56.200
This school is very quiet when I'm ready to leave.

06:56.200 --> 07:00.200
I'm glad because I don't want to see anybody.

07:00.200 --> 07:05.200
But before I go home, I need to know that Rosie is okay.

07:05.200 --> 07:11.200
When I get to the nurse's office, Jane and Julie are standing in front of the door.

07:11.200 --> 07:15.200
When they see me, they stop talking.

07:15.200 --> 07:17.200
What do you want?

07:17.200 --> 07:18.200
asks Jane.

07:18.200 --> 07:20.200
She doesn't smile.

07:20.200 --> 07:23.200
I... I want to see Rosie.

07:23.200 --> 07:26.200
I want to see if she's okay, I say.

07:26.200 --> 07:29.200
Well, she doesn't want to see you.

07:29.200 --> 07:31.200
Mrs. Julie.

07:31.200 --> 07:34.200
Please, I say moving towards the door.

07:34.200 --> 07:39.200
But they stand closer together, stopping me from going in.

07:39.200 --> 07:42.200
Don't you understand, says Jane.

07:42.200 --> 07:49.200
She doesn't want to see you.

07:49.200 --> 07:53.200
I open my mouth to say something horrible to them.

07:53.200 --> 07:56.200
But if I try to speak, I will cry.

07:56.200 --> 07:59.200
And I will not cry in front of those two.

07:59.200 --> 08:01.200
So I walk away.

08:01.200 --> 08:05.200
When I turn the corner, I start to cry.

08:05.200 --> 08:07.200
And then I start to run.

08:07.200 --> 08:09.200
I hate this school.

08:09.200 --> 08:12.200
I never want to come back.

08:12.200 --> 08:13.200
Never!

08:13.200 --> 08:16.200
I run away from the school.

08:16.200 --> 08:20.200
And when I turn a corner, I run straight into Sarah.

08:20.200 --> 08:23.200
She's coming out of the library with some books.

08:23.200 --> 08:25.200
And they all fall to the ground.

08:25.200 --> 08:29.200
Sorry, I say, as I help her pick up the books.

08:29.200 --> 08:32.200
Advanced German grammar.

08:32.200 --> 08:34.200
Genetics today.

08:34.200 --> 08:37.200
Sarah is my best friend.

08:37.200 --> 08:43.200
The only problem is, her idea of fun is extra chemistry homework.

08:43.200 --> 08:46.200
I heard about the basketball match.

08:46.200 --> 08:49.200
I'm sorry you didn't win, but it wasn't your fault.

08:49.200 --> 08:51.200
I try to smile.

08:52.200 --> 08:55.200
I know she's only trying to make me feel better.

08:55.200 --> 08:57.200
But then she continues.

08:57.200 --> 09:02.200
I mean, Miss Stevens knows you're not very good at taking penalties.

09:02.200 --> 09:06.200
She sees the look on my face and quickly says...

09:06.200 --> 09:11.200
But you were good at other things, like, um, French.

09:11.200 --> 09:12.200
No, really.

09:12.200 --> 09:15.200
You did really well in the last test.

09:15.200 --> 09:18.200
Sarah, I got a C.

09:19.200 --> 09:22.200
Well, that's good for you.

09:22.200 --> 09:25.200
After a pause, she tries again.

09:25.200 --> 09:28.200
That's it, she says.

09:28.200 --> 09:32.200
Just as Einstein probably did when he made his discoveries.

09:32.200 --> 09:34.200
The baking.

09:34.200 --> 09:38.200
Your chocolate cake is the best in the world.

09:38.200 --> 09:41.200
We walk the rest of the way home in silence.

09:41.200 --> 09:45.200
I'm going to the fair with my parents tomorrow night.

09:45.200 --> 09:47.200
She says when we get to my house.

09:47.200 --> 09:50.200
Do you want to come with us?

09:50.200 --> 09:53.200
Maybe it will make you feel better.

09:53.200 --> 09:59.200
Sarah is the only teenager on the planet who will be going to the fair with her mum and dad.

09:59.200 --> 10:01.200
But I have nothing better to do.

10:01.200 --> 10:04.200
Excellent, she says.

10:04.200 --> 10:07.200
And with a big smile, she walks away.

10:07.200 --> 10:12.200
Later that evening, mum and I sit down to have dinner.

10:12.200 --> 10:15.200
Some people don't eat anything when they're sad.

10:15.200 --> 10:19.200
Some people are never sad because their lives are perfect.

10:19.200 --> 10:22.200
People like Rosie, for example.

10:22.200 --> 10:26.200
That's why they can live on half a carrot a day.

10:26.200 --> 10:32.200
But other people, like me, when things go wrong, they bake.

10:32.200 --> 10:36.200
And when they're finished baking, they bake some more.

10:36.200 --> 10:40.200
And then they sit down and eat the lot.

10:40.200 --> 10:44.200
When dad comes home, he sits down at the table with the big smile.

10:44.200 --> 10:47.200
Ready to hear my news and asks.

10:47.200 --> 10:50.200
How's my little champion?

10:50.200 --> 10:53.200
Mum puts his plate in front of him and says.

10:53.200 --> 10:56.200
I always thought basketball was a silly game.

10:56.200 --> 10:58.200
Never mind, Holly.

10:58.200 --> 11:02.200
It's your birthday on Sunday and Monday is a bank holiday.

11:02.200 --> 11:06.200
Dad knows then that things didn't go well.

11:06.200 --> 11:08.200
He stops smiling.

11:08.200 --> 11:12.200
Oh, well, I'm sure you did your best.

11:12.200 --> 11:16.200
He says, I only played for 30 seconds.

11:16.200 --> 11:19.200
Well, it can't be your fault then, can it?

11:19.200 --> 11:21.200
He smiles again.

11:21.200 --> 11:23.200
I missed a penalty.

11:23.200 --> 11:24.200
Oh.

11:24.200 --> 11:26.200
No smile.

11:26.200 --> 11:32.200
In the last minute of the game, after a long silence, he says.

11:32.200 --> 11:36.200
But your chocolate cake is the best in the world.

11:36.200 --> 11:40.200
He smiles once more and reaches for the salt.

11:40.200 --> 11:44.200
Later, I sit in bed eating chocolate ice cream.

11:44.200 --> 11:49.200
Why can't anyone understand that I don't want to be known because I make nice cakes?

11:49.200 --> 11:53.200
I want to be funny, pretty, clever.

11:53.200 --> 11:58.200
No one will ever want to go to the fair or anywhere else with me now.

11:58.200 --> 12:02.200
No one except Sarah and her mum and dad.

12:02.200 --> 12:04.200
Why is life so wrong?

12:04.200 --> 12:06.200
Why?

12:06.200 --> 12:08.200
Why?

12:08.200 --> 12:11.200
I don't hear the phone ringing.

12:11.200 --> 12:14.200
Holly, there's a call for you.

12:14.200 --> 12:16.200
Shouts mum.

12:16.200 --> 12:18.200
Say that I'm sleeping.

12:18.200 --> 12:20.200
I shout back.

12:20.200 --> 12:22.200
It's a boy called Ben.

12:22.200 --> 12:25.200
He says he goes to your school.

12:25.200 --> 12:27.200
Are you sure?

12:27.200 --> 12:32.200
Before she can continue, I'm out of bed and running down the stairs.

12:32.200 --> 12:33.200
Hello?

12:33.200 --> 12:35.200
Hello, Holly.

12:35.200 --> 12:38.200
I just wanted to know how you're feeling.

12:38.200 --> 12:43.200
You looked really disappointed after the match, but it wasn't your fault.

12:43.200 --> 12:45.200
Er, I...

12:45.200 --> 12:48.200
Do you want to go to the fair tomorrow night?

12:48.200 --> 12:50.200
He says quickly.

12:50.200 --> 12:52.200
It seems like he's nervous.

12:52.200 --> 12:53.200
I...

12:53.200 --> 12:58.200
A group of us are going and I thought, well, I'd...

12:58.200 --> 13:00.200
I'd really like you to come too.

13:00.200 --> 13:03.200
Holly, are you still there?

13:03.200 --> 13:04.200
Yes.

13:04.200 --> 13:07.200
Oh, why can't I be like Rosie?

13:07.200 --> 13:11.200
She's never nervous when she speaks to boys.

13:11.200 --> 13:13.200
I mean, what time?

13:13.200 --> 13:15.200
We can meet there at six.

13:15.200 --> 13:17.200
Is that okay?

13:17.200 --> 13:18.200
Okay.

13:18.200 --> 13:21.200
I'm going out with Ben.

13:21.200 --> 13:24.200
I'm going out with Ben.

13:24.200 --> 13:25.200
Bye.

13:25.200 --> 13:26.200
Bye.

13:26.200 --> 13:28.200
Oh, and Holly?

13:28.200 --> 13:29.200
Yes.

13:29.200 --> 13:32.200
I'm really glad you said yes.

13:32.200 --> 13:34.200
And then he hangs up.

13:34.200 --> 13:38.200
And like an idiot, I stand there, holding onto the phone.

13:38.200 --> 13:41.200
My heart beating strong and loud.

13:41.200 --> 13:43.200
My legs feeling weak as jelly.

13:43.200 --> 13:47.200
But wanting to dance around the room all at the same time.

13:47.200 --> 13:51.200
I don't have bad memories of the match now.

13:54.200 --> 13:56.200
Listening activity.

13:57.200 --> 13:59.200
Hello.

13:59.200 --> 14:00.200
Hello.

14:00.200 --> 14:02.200
Can I speak to Amy, please?

14:02.200 --> 14:03.200
Speaking.

14:03.200 --> 14:04.200
Hi, Amy.

14:04.200 --> 14:05.200
It's Mark.

14:05.200 --> 14:06.200
Hi, Mark.

14:06.200 --> 14:07.200
How are you?

14:07.200 --> 14:09.200
I'm fine, thanks.

14:09.200 --> 14:11.200
I was going to phone you after tea.

14:11.200 --> 14:14.200
Are you going to Lucy's birthday party?

14:14.200 --> 14:17.200
I wanted to, but my dad has got to go to work.

14:17.200 --> 14:19.200
He can't take me.

14:19.200 --> 14:22.200
We can pick you up if you want.

14:22.200 --> 14:23.200
Really?

14:23.200 --> 14:25.200
That would be great.

14:25.200 --> 14:26.200
Sure.

14:26.200 --> 14:27.200
I'll check with Dad.

14:27.200 --> 14:29.200
But I'm sure it'll be okay.

14:29.200 --> 14:30.200
What time?

14:30.200 --> 14:32.200
The party starts at six.

14:32.200 --> 14:35.200
What about quarter two then?

14:35.200 --> 14:37.200
We don't want to get there first.

14:37.200 --> 14:38.200
Okay.

14:38.200 --> 14:39.200
Quarter to six.

14:39.200 --> 14:40.200
See you then.

14:40.200 --> 14:41.200
Bye.

14:41.200 --> 14:42.200
Bye.

14:42.200 --> 14:43.200
Chapter three.

14:43.200 --> 14:44.200
Friends again.

14:44.200 --> 14:45.200
Thank you.

14:45.200 --> 14:46.200
Thank you.

14:46.200 --> 14:47.200
Thank you.

14:47.200 --> 14:48.200
Thank you.

14:48.200 --> 14:49.200
Thank you.

14:50.200 --> 14:52.200
Chapter three.

14:52.200 --> 14:55.200
Friends again.

14:55.200 --> 15:00.200
The next morning, a knock on my bedroom door wakes me up.

15:00.200 --> 15:04.200
Just when I was having a wonderful dream about Ben.

15:04.200 --> 15:06.200
I want to go back to sleep.

15:06.200 --> 15:08.200
Back to my dream.

15:08.200 --> 15:10.200
But then Rosie is in my room.

15:10.200 --> 15:12.200
I wanted to come and see you.

15:12.200 --> 15:15.200
Aunt Violet said it was okay.

15:15.200 --> 15:17.200
You don't mind, do you?

15:17.200 --> 15:19.200
She looks like she's sorry.

15:19.200 --> 15:22.200
She looks like she wants to be friends.

15:22.200 --> 15:25.200
She doesn't look like Rosie at all.

15:25.200 --> 15:26.200
How's your foot?

15:26.200 --> 15:27.200
I ask.

15:27.200 --> 15:31.200
I tried to hide last night's empty ice cream box.

15:31.200 --> 15:34.200
I see the spoon just before Rosie sits on it.

15:34.200 --> 15:37.200
I tried to come and see you.

15:37.200 --> 15:39.200
But Jane and Julie...

15:39.200 --> 15:40.200
I know.

15:40.200 --> 15:42.200
That's why I'm here.

15:42.200 --> 15:44.200
She holds my hand.

15:44.200 --> 15:47.200
I was horrible to you yesterday.

15:47.200 --> 15:48.200
We all were.

15:48.200 --> 15:50.200
That's okay.

15:50.200 --> 15:52.200
Let's forget about it.

15:52.200 --> 15:53.200
Really?

15:53.200 --> 15:55.200
I smile.

15:55.200 --> 15:56.200
Really?

15:56.200 --> 16:00.200
Can I do anything to show you how sorry I am?

16:00.200 --> 16:01.200
Anything at all.

16:01.200 --> 16:04.200
Do you want to come and see the new house?

16:04.200 --> 16:06.200
You can use our gym and sauna.

16:06.200 --> 16:08.200
I want to say yes.

16:08.200 --> 16:11.200
But then I see myself in the mirror.

16:11.200 --> 16:15.200
The last thing I want is Rosie to see me in a swimming costume.

16:15.200 --> 16:17.200
I look at Rosie sitting next to me.

16:17.200 --> 16:19.200
Perfect as usual.

16:19.200 --> 16:23.200
I think for a moment and then I have an idea.

16:23.200 --> 16:27.200
Actually, there is something.

16:27.200 --> 16:31.200
Two hours later we are in one of Rosie's favorite shops.

16:31.200 --> 16:33.200
But I can't buy it.

16:33.200 --> 16:35.200
It's very short.

16:35.200 --> 16:37.200
My dad will ground me.

16:37.200 --> 16:40.200
Trust me, says Rosie.

16:40.200 --> 16:42.200
It's the latest fashion.

16:42.200 --> 16:50.200
You can't go out with the most gorgeous boy in school wearing something that your dad likes.

16:50.200 --> 16:53.200
Well, I suppose not.

16:53.200 --> 16:55.200
Oh no!

16:55.200 --> 16:56.200
What?

16:56.200 --> 16:59.200
I know it's not cheap, but...

16:59.200 --> 17:00.200
Shhh!

17:00.200 --> 17:02.200
It's Sarah!

17:02.200 --> 17:05.200
I say looking desperately for somewhere to hide.

17:05.200 --> 17:06.200
So?

17:06.200 --> 17:09.200
She thinks that I'm going to the fair with her tonight.

17:09.200 --> 17:10.200
And?

17:10.200 --> 17:11.200
Quick!

17:11.200 --> 17:12.200
Hide behind!

17:12.200 --> 17:13.200
Oh no!

17:13.200 --> 17:16.200
It's too late she can see us!

17:16.200 --> 17:20.200
Tell her that you're going to grams because she's not very well.

17:20.200 --> 17:22.200
I can't do that!

17:22.200 --> 17:25.200
But then Sarah is in the shop.

17:25.200 --> 17:28.200
I want to go out with Ben more than anything.

17:28.200 --> 17:31.200
But I can't lie to my best friend.

17:31.200 --> 17:33.200
Can I?

17:33.200 --> 17:34.200
Hi, Holly.

17:34.200 --> 17:36.200
I thought it was you.

17:36.200 --> 17:39.200
She says with a big smile.

17:39.200 --> 17:40.200
Rosie.

17:40.200 --> 17:43.200
She says, but without a smile.

17:43.200 --> 17:46.200
I'm really looking forward to tonight.

17:46.200 --> 17:50.200
Mum says she'll take us for a pizza first too.

17:50.200 --> 17:53.200
Actually, I...

17:53.200 --> 17:56.200
I need to talk to you about tonight.

17:56.200 --> 17:58.200
I...

17:58.200 --> 17:59.200
I can't.

17:59.200 --> 18:02.200
I can't come to the fair, you see.

18:02.200 --> 18:04.200
I feel terrible.

18:05.200 --> 18:09.200
But the words are out of my mouth before I can stop them.

18:09.200 --> 18:11.200
It's my grand.

18:11.200 --> 18:13.200
She's sick and needs me.

18:13.200 --> 18:15.200
You know how it is.

18:15.200 --> 18:16.200
Oh.

18:16.200 --> 18:19.200
Well, I hope she feels better soon.

18:19.200 --> 18:22.200
She looks so disappointed.

18:22.200 --> 18:24.200
And I feel terrible.

18:24.200 --> 18:26.200
I've got to go.

18:26.200 --> 18:28.200
See you tomorrow.

18:28.200 --> 18:33.200
I say quickly and walk away before she can see my red face.

18:33.200 --> 18:37.200
When we get back home, it's already late afternoon.

18:37.200 --> 18:42.200
Rosie puts some music on and does my hair and makeup.

18:42.200 --> 18:44.200
Then I put on my new clothes.

18:44.200 --> 18:48.200
I'm excited and I soon forget about Sarah.

18:48.200 --> 18:49.200
There.

18:49.200 --> 18:51.200
All finished.

18:51.200 --> 18:53.200
Says Rosie happily.

18:53.200 --> 18:54.200
What do you think?

18:54.200 --> 18:57.200
I don't really like purple eyeshadow.

18:57.200 --> 19:00.200
And the orange top is very tight.

19:00.200 --> 19:01.200
Well?

19:01.200 --> 19:04.200
She asks, waiting for my answer.

19:04.200 --> 19:08.200
It's great, I say, and try to smile.

19:08.200 --> 19:13.200
But there is so much makeup on my face that I can't smile too much.

19:13.200 --> 19:16.200
Ben will love it.

19:16.200 --> 19:17.200
Trust me.

19:17.200 --> 19:19.200
Are you going to the fair too?

19:19.200 --> 19:22.200
I ask, trying to keep calm.

19:22.200 --> 19:25.200
In 24 minutes, I'm meeting Ben.

19:25.200 --> 19:27.200
No, my foot hurts.

19:27.200 --> 19:30.200
I'm going home to watch a DVD.

19:30.200 --> 19:32.200
That's not much fun.

19:32.200 --> 19:34.200
I say as we go out the door.

19:34.200 --> 19:36.200
Don't worry about me.

19:36.200 --> 19:38.200
Just have a good time.

19:38.200 --> 19:41.200
She says, thanks Rosie.

19:41.200 --> 19:43.200
I say as I get on the bus.

19:43.200 --> 19:47.200
Rosie smiles and waves as I sit down.

19:47.200 --> 19:52.200
I'm not surprised her foot hurts after shopping all day.

19:52.200 --> 19:58.200
Rosie continues waving and then the bus turns the corner.

19:58.200 --> 20:04.200
But when the bus disappears, her smile disappears too.

20:04.200 --> 20:09.200
She takes her mobile phone and calls Julie.

20:09.200 --> 20:17.200
Everything is perfect, she says.

20:17.200 --> 20:19.200
Chapter 4.

20:19.200 --> 20:22.200
The Truth

20:22.200 --> 20:26.200
When I get off the bus, I'm really excited.

20:26.200 --> 20:29.200
I even say goodbye to the bus driver.

20:29.200 --> 20:34.200
But when I get to the fair, Ben isn't there.

20:34.200 --> 20:39.200
I sit down on a bench just outside the entrance and look at my watch.

20:39.200 --> 20:41.200
Again.

20:41.200 --> 20:43.200
605.

20:43.200 --> 20:46.200
Is Ben excited like me?

20:46.200 --> 20:48.200
615.

20:48.200 --> 20:53.200
I watch people go in, families, groups of friends and couples holding hands.

20:53.200 --> 20:56.200
Will Ben hold my hand?

20:56.200 --> 20:58.200
615.

20:58.200 --> 21:00.200
Maybe his bus is late.

21:00.200 --> 21:04.200
Traffic is usually bad at this time of day.

21:04.200 --> 21:06.200
630.

21:06.200 --> 21:09.200
Where are you, Ben?

21:09.200 --> 21:12.200
633.

21:12.200 --> 21:17.200
Maybe his parents are angry with him for some reason and they won't let him go out.

21:17.200 --> 21:22.200
And because he hasn't got my mobile number, he can't call me.

21:22.200 --> 21:25.200
634.

21:25.200 --> 21:29.200
Why didn't I give him my mobile number?

21:29.200 --> 21:31.200
635.

21:31.200 --> 21:34.200
Why didn't I ask for his?

21:34.200 --> 21:37.200
645.

21:37.200 --> 21:43.200
Did he say that he's going to meet me outside the fair or inside?

21:43.200 --> 21:46.200
I was so excited when he phoned.

21:46.200 --> 21:48.200
I can't remember.

21:49.200 --> 21:52.200
Maybe he's inside thinking that I'm not coming.

21:52.200 --> 21:56.200
I quickly get up and go through the entrance.

21:56.200 --> 22:02.200
The loud music and bright lights make everything seem magical as I look for Ben.

22:02.200 --> 22:03.200
Holy!

22:03.200 --> 22:07.200
Someone calls my name, but it isn't Ben.

22:07.200 --> 22:11.200
I thought your gran was sick, Holy.

22:11.200 --> 22:13.200
Sarah!

22:13.200 --> 22:17.200
I... I say and my face goes red.

22:18.200 --> 22:20.200
You lied to me.

22:20.200 --> 22:23.200
She says, her mum and dad look at me.

22:23.200 --> 22:27.200
They seem more disappointed than angry.

22:27.200 --> 22:33.200
I suddenly feel very silly in the short skirt and makeup that Rosie gave me.

22:33.200 --> 22:35.200
I can explain.

22:35.200 --> 22:42.200
I try to touch her arm, but she moves away, her eyes full of angry tears.

22:42.200 --> 22:44.200
I'm not interested.

22:45.200 --> 22:47.200
I thought you were my friend.

22:47.200 --> 22:49.200
My best friend.

22:49.200 --> 22:53.200
She says, and then walks away.

22:53.200 --> 22:57.200
I stand there alone and I feel stupid.

22:57.200 --> 23:01.200
First the basketball match, then Ben.

23:01.200 --> 23:04.200
And now Sarah isn't my friend anymore.

23:04.200 --> 23:06.200
What's the matter, Holly?

23:06.200 --> 23:08.200
Someone says behind me.

23:08.200 --> 23:10.200
It's Rosie.

23:10.200 --> 23:14.200
Oh Rosie, I'm so glad to see you.

23:14.200 --> 23:15.200
Ben didn't.

23:15.200 --> 23:19.200
But before I finish, I can hear laughter.

23:19.200 --> 23:22.200
Horrible, horrible laughter.

23:22.200 --> 23:31.200
The laughter is coming from Rosie's friends.

23:31.200 --> 23:38.200
For a moment, I just stand there while they laugh and point at me my silly clothes and my terrible makeup.

23:38.200 --> 23:41.200
How could I be so stupid?

23:41.200 --> 23:43.200
I thought she was my friend.

23:43.200 --> 23:47.200
I thought she was nice and wanted to help me.

23:47.200 --> 23:51.200
Did you really believe that Ben wants to go out with you?

23:51.200 --> 23:52.200
She says.

23:57.200 --> 24:01.200
She starts to laugh again and her friends laugh even louder.

24:01.200 --> 24:04.200
And louder and louder.

24:04.200 --> 24:07.200
I turn and start to run.

24:07.200 --> 24:09.200
This is a nightmare.

24:09.200 --> 24:11.200
I'll wake up soon.

24:11.200 --> 24:13.200
I'll wake up soon.

24:13.200 --> 24:17.200
I tell myself again and again.

24:17.200 --> 24:21.200
But I know that I will remember tonight forever.

24:21.200 --> 24:24.200
When I am alone, I sit down on a bench.

24:24.200 --> 24:31.200
Then I realize that it is the same bench as before and I start to cry.

24:31.200 --> 24:34.200
I was so happy then.

24:34.200 --> 24:38.200
It was only half an hour ago, but it seems more like ten years.

24:38.200 --> 24:42.200
How can everything change so quickly?

24:42.200 --> 24:45.200
Are you okay?

24:45.200 --> 24:47.200
An old woman asks me.

24:47.200 --> 24:50.200
I look up quickly.

24:50.200 --> 24:54.200
She's sitting next to me, a grey cat on her knee.

24:54.200 --> 25:00.200
I can tell you your future if you want.

25:00.200 --> 25:03.200
I don't want to know about my future.

25:03.200 --> 25:05.200
I have no future.

25:05.200 --> 25:10.200
I stand up and start to walk away, ready to go home.

25:10.200 --> 25:14.200
But if you can make wishes come true, I think.

25:14.200 --> 25:18.200
Five pounds.

25:18.200 --> 25:20.200
Says the old woman.

25:20.200 --> 25:25.200
Something in her voice makes me stop walking and take my purse out of my bag.

25:25.200 --> 25:33.200
I can make wishes come true for five pounds.

25:33.200 --> 25:37.200
I've only got five pounds, I say.

25:37.200 --> 25:41.200
But when I look up, the old woman is not there anymore.

25:41.200 --> 25:46.200
I don't know why, but I am happy when I see her standing outside a caravan.

25:46.200 --> 25:48.200
The cat in her arms.

25:48.200 --> 25:52.200
Another three cats move hungrily between her legs.

25:52.200 --> 25:56.200
How did she get that far so quickly?

25:56.200 --> 26:01.200
I don't know why I don't just go home, but I walk towards her.

26:01.200 --> 26:10.200
I give her the money, she opens the door, and I go inside the caravan.

26:10.200 --> 26:14.200
Listening activity.

26:14.200 --> 26:16.200
One.

26:16.200 --> 26:20.200
What time is Holly going to meet Ben?

26:21.200 --> 26:24.200
Would you like to go to the fair, Holly?

26:24.200 --> 26:26.200
Yes, that would be great.

26:26.200 --> 26:28.200
What time?

26:28.200 --> 26:30.200
How about six o'clock?

26:30.200 --> 26:32.200
I'm not sure.

26:32.200 --> 26:35.200
I've got a doctor's appointment at half past five.

26:35.200 --> 26:38.200
How about a quarter to seven then?

26:38.200 --> 26:39.200
Excellent.

26:39.200 --> 26:42.200
See you then.

26:42.200 --> 26:44.200
Two.

26:44.200 --> 26:48.200
What time is Sarah's train leaving today?

26:48.200 --> 26:50.200
Excuse me.

26:50.200 --> 26:54.200
Can you tell me what time the train to London is, please?

26:54.200 --> 26:57.200
Just one moment, please.

26:57.200 --> 27:00.200
There's one at three ten.

27:00.200 --> 27:02.200
That's too early.

27:02.200 --> 27:04.200
Is there a later train?

27:04.200 --> 27:05.200
Yes.

27:05.200 --> 27:11.200
The next train to London leaves at three fifty, but there's a one hour delay.

27:11.200 --> 27:12.200
Okay.

27:12.200 --> 27:13.200
Thank you.

27:13.200 --> 27:15.200
Bye.

27:15.200 --> 27:17.200
Three.

27:17.200 --> 27:21.200
What time does Rose's party start?

27:21.200 --> 27:24.200
Are you going to Rose's party, Julie?

27:24.200 --> 27:28.200
I'd like to, but I've got to see my grand in the afternoon.

27:28.200 --> 27:31.200
I won't leave her house until six.

27:31.200 --> 27:33.200
That's okay.

27:33.200 --> 27:37.200
It starts at seven thirty, but I'm not going until eight o'clock.

27:37.200 --> 27:39.200
Do you want to go together?

27:39.200 --> 27:41.200
That's a good idea.

27:41.200 --> 27:42.200
I can't wait.

27:42.200 --> 27:44.200
Me too.

27:44.200 --> 27:47.200
Bye.

27:47.200 --> 27:52.200
Travelling Funfares

27:52.200 --> 28:00.200
Groups of people called Shoman travel throughout the year to different areas of the country to set up funfares.

28:00.200 --> 28:06.200
These are called travelling funfares because they do not stay in the same place.

28:06.200 --> 28:13.200
The type of funfares that always stays in the same place is called a theme park.

28:13.200 --> 28:18.200
Funfares are very popular all over Britain and in many other places in the world.

28:18.200 --> 28:24.200
They are especially popular with teenagers and families with young children.

28:24.200 --> 28:28.200
Each funfair has a lot of different rides.

28:28.200 --> 28:36.200
There are rides for adults and older children and teenagers, sometimes called thrill rides.

28:36.200 --> 28:47.200
These rides move very fast, going backwards and forwards, up and down and often use a lot of spinning or falling.

28:47.200 --> 28:52.200
They are a lot of fun, but are also very scary.

28:52.200 --> 28:58.200
There are also lots of rides for younger children, such as train rides.

28:58.200 --> 29:03.200
These are slower and not scary.

29:03.200 --> 29:08.200
There are stalls where you can play games, such as throwing games.

29:08.200 --> 29:13.200
At these stalls, people pay to complete a task.

29:13.200 --> 29:17.200
For example, hitting some moving objects with a ball.

29:17.200 --> 29:26.200
If the person is successful, he or she wins a prize, often a giant teddy bear.

29:26.200 --> 29:36.200
These stalls are very popular with teenage couples, because it is considered romantic for a boy to win a prize for his girlfriend.

29:36.200 --> 29:40.200
There are other stalls where you can buy food.

29:40.200 --> 29:49.200
Hot dogs, hamburgers and chips are popular, but candy floss is the traditional funfair food.

29:49.200 --> 29:53.200
Most funfares also have a fortune teller.

29:53.200 --> 30:01.200
This person, usually a woman, tells a person what will happen to him or her in the future.

30:01.200 --> 30:07.200
Sometimes these things come true, but sometimes they don't.

30:07.200 --> 30:10.200
Do you believe in fortune tellers?

30:10.200 --> 30:16.200
Hoppings, Europe's largest travelling funfair.

30:16.200 --> 30:24.200
Throughout the year, town more, in Newcastle-upon-Tine, is home to about 400 cows.

30:24.200 --> 30:32.200
But for a week in June, the 30 acre space is covered with over 60 rides and numerous stalls.

30:32.200 --> 30:40.200
Travelling fairs from all parts of the country come together, and the Hoppings happens.

30:40.200 --> 30:47.200
This funfair began in 1882 and has over a million visitors each year.

30:47.200 --> 30:50.200
It is now bigger than ever.

30:53.200 --> 30:57.200
Chapter 5 Make a Wish

30:59.200 --> 31:05.200
Are you sure you want things to change, Holly?

31:05.200 --> 31:07.200
The old woman asks me.

31:07.200 --> 31:11.200
Yes, I'm totally sure, I say.

31:11.200 --> 31:17.200
The old woman looks at me for a long time, then she takes a birthday cake out of the fridge.

31:17.200 --> 31:23.200
It looks delicious, and in the middle there is one pink candle.

31:23.200 --> 31:28.200
She puts the cake on the table in front of me and lights the candle.

31:28.200 --> 31:32.200
Then, very quietly, she says.

31:32.200 --> 31:36.200
Happy birthday, Holly.

31:36.200 --> 31:42.200
Blow out the candle and make your wish.

31:42.200 --> 31:48.200
It all feels very strange, like I'm watching it all on television.

31:48.200 --> 31:55.200
I close my eyes and blow out the candle, repeating my wish again and again to myself.

31:55.200 --> 32:01.200
When I open my eyes, for a moment everything is black, there is nothing.

32:01.200 --> 32:05.200
And then everything starts to become clear again.

32:05.200 --> 32:13.200
First the lights of the fair shine through the closed curtains, and then there is the tick-tock of the clock on the wall.

32:13.200 --> 32:16.200
But I am alone in the caravan.

32:16.200 --> 32:20.200
The old woman and her cats are no longer here.

32:20.200 --> 32:23.200
I stand up quickly and run outside.

32:23.200 --> 32:28.200
I want to call out for her, but I don't know her name.

32:28.200 --> 32:30.200
I don't feel different.

32:30.200 --> 32:32.200
The wish isn't working.

32:32.200 --> 32:36.200
How could I believe that the old woman can change my life?

32:36.200 --> 32:43.200
How could I believe that Rosie wanted to be my friend, or that Ben really wanted to go out with me?

32:43.200 --> 32:46.200
I must be really stupid.

32:46.200 --> 32:49.200
And I gave her five pounds.

32:49.200 --> 32:51.200
Rosie!

32:51.200 --> 32:54.200
A voice calls from far away.

32:54.200 --> 32:59.200
But then, how did the old woman know it's my birthday tomorrow?

32:59.200 --> 33:01.200
Rosie!

33:01.200 --> 33:04.200
Says the voice closer now.

33:04.200 --> 33:06.200
And how did she know my name?

33:06.200 --> 33:08.200
Did I tell her?

33:08.200 --> 33:10.200
I don't think so.

33:10.200 --> 33:13.200
Maybe this is all another trick.

33:13.200 --> 33:16.200
Someone touches my arm and says again.

33:16.200 --> 33:18.200
Rosie!

33:18.200 --> 33:20.200
I quickly turn around.

33:20.200 --> 33:23.200
Julie and Jane are standing in front of me.

33:23.200 --> 33:25.200
Aren't you here, us?

33:25.200 --> 33:26.200
Julie says.

33:26.200 --> 33:28.200
What are you doing here?

33:28.200 --> 33:29.200
Are you okay?

33:29.200 --> 33:32.200
You look a little strange.

33:32.200 --> 33:34.200
I...

33:34.200 --> 33:37.200
That was a great trick.

33:37.200 --> 33:40.200
She says and starts to laugh.

33:40.200 --> 33:43.200
Everyone at school is going to laugh at this.

33:43.200 --> 33:45.200
That's good!

33:45.200 --> 33:49.200
Why didn't I take a photo with my mobile phone?

33:49.200 --> 33:52.200
But I don't hear her anymore.

33:52.200 --> 33:54.200
Behind Julie there is a mirror.

33:54.200 --> 34:01.200
And the girl looking back at me, her blonde hair is perfect, long and straight.

34:01.200 --> 34:03.200
Not like a clown's hair.

34:03.200 --> 34:06.200
My wish really did come true.

34:06.200 --> 34:08.200
I'm Rosie!

34:08.200 --> 34:10.200
I'm Rosie!

34:10.200 --> 34:15.200
Being Rosie is the best feeling in the world.

34:15.200 --> 34:18.200
When I was Holly, nobody noticed me.

34:18.200 --> 34:25.200
But now that I'm Rosie, everybody wants to talk to me, ask what I think can be my friend.

34:25.200 --> 34:30.200
I smile and laugh, and I don't feel scared of what people think about me.

34:30.200 --> 34:34.200
I'm Rosie, and I feel like I could run a marathon.

34:34.200 --> 34:36.200
Kind man-teverest.

34:36.200 --> 34:38.200
I could do anything.

34:38.200 --> 34:40.200
Another voice shouts.

34:40.200 --> 34:43.200
Rosie! Rosie!

34:43.200 --> 34:45.200
It's Ben.

34:45.200 --> 34:48.200
He's running, and he looks very worried.

34:48.200 --> 34:51.200
But he's still gorgeous.

34:51.200 --> 34:55.200
I feel more like Holly again as I try to say something.

34:55.200 --> 34:57.200
Do you know if Holly is here?

34:57.200 --> 34:58.200
He asks.

34:58.200 --> 35:02.200
I couldn't find that DVD you said I had Rosie.

35:02.200 --> 35:04.200
Are you sure you gave it to me?

35:04.200 --> 35:07.200
I still don't know why you needed it tonight.

35:07.200 --> 35:10.200
Oh, I hope Holly's still here.

35:10.200 --> 35:13.200
He says, looking around.

35:13.200 --> 35:17.200
Julian, Jane, start to laugh.

35:19.200 --> 35:20.200
What?

35:20.200 --> 35:21.200
Says Ben.

35:21.200 --> 35:22.200
Why are you laughing?

35:22.200 --> 35:24.200
What's so funny?

35:24.200 --> 35:28.200
Ben, his eyes become cold, and he looks at me angrily.

35:28.200 --> 35:31.200
What did you do to her, Rosie?

35:31.200 --> 35:32.200
Me?

35:32.200 --> 35:33.200
I...

35:33.200 --> 35:37.200
It was so funny, Ben.

35:37.200 --> 35:38.200
Says Julie.

35:38.200 --> 35:41.200
There was no DVD, Rosie, right?

35:41.200 --> 35:48.680
And he says coldly, I, everyone quickly stops laughing.

35:48.680 --> 35:51.920
They turn to look at me as Ben walks away.

35:51.920 --> 35:54.120
I start to become red.

35:54.120 --> 35:58.320
I want to shout after him that I'm really holly, not Rosie.

35:58.320 --> 36:00.280
It wasn't me who did this.

36:00.280 --> 36:02.320
I didn't do it.

36:02.320 --> 36:05.120
But who will believe me?

36:05.120 --> 36:08.000
After that nothing seems the same.

36:08.000 --> 36:09.560
Everyone starts to go home.

36:09.920 --> 36:11.920
It's 11 p.m.

36:11.920 --> 36:14.040
I never go home this late.

36:14.040 --> 36:17.240
My dad will definitely ground me.

36:17.240 --> 36:23.000
But as I run towards home, I suddenly realize, I'm Rosie now.

36:23.000 --> 36:25.840
I have to go to Rosie's house.

36:25.840 --> 36:29.600
Rosie's new house is the biggest in the village.

36:29.600 --> 36:34.200
A friend say it even has a swimming pool and six servants.

36:34.200 --> 36:37.680
It will be fun to live the life of the rich girl, the girl who

36:37.720 --> 36:39.560
has everything.

36:39.560 --> 36:42.960
But when I get back, the front door is locked.

36:42.960 --> 36:44.800
The lights are all out.

36:44.800 --> 36:47.520
It looks like nobody's at home.

36:47.520 --> 36:52.480
I knock again, louder this time, but there is still no answer.

36:52.480 --> 36:55.320
Where are my aunt and uncle?

36:55.320 --> 36:57.280
I look in Rosie's bag.

36:57.280 --> 37:02.240
At the bottom, I find a key, and I go inside.

37:02.240 --> 37:04.680
The first thing I notice about the house

37:04.680 --> 37:07.280
is that it is huge.

37:07.280 --> 37:09.320
I start to look around.

37:09.320 --> 37:14.760
There are a lot of beautiful things, but there are no family photos.

37:14.760 --> 37:18.200
There are lots of photos in every room of my house.

37:18.200 --> 37:21.440
Everything here is perfect and expensive.

37:21.440 --> 37:26.200
But there is no love, and it feels cold.

37:26.200 --> 37:30.280
I go upstairs, but still there are no angry parents.

37:30.280 --> 37:35.000
My mom and dad are always angry with me when I come back late.

37:35.000 --> 37:38.400
But now, as I get into Rosie's bed,

37:38.400 --> 37:41.640
I would like that more than anything.

37:41.640 --> 37:44.600
I want them to shout, be angry.

37:44.600 --> 37:45.880
Anything.

37:45.880 --> 37:47.400
I just want them here.

37:51.480 --> 37:53.720
Chapter 6.

37:53.720 --> 37:54.640
Happy birthday.

37:57.520 --> 38:02.040
I can't sleep, so I get up early the next morning.

38:02.040 --> 38:05.960
I choose some of Rosie's expensive clothes to wear.

38:05.960 --> 38:10.280
I always like Rosie's clothes, but when I look in the mirror,

38:10.280 --> 38:13.120
there is no smile on my face.

38:13.120 --> 38:17.080
Today's our birthday, Rosie, I say to myself.

38:17.080 --> 38:18.960
I'm sure that Aunt Lillian, Uncle Pete,

38:18.960 --> 38:21.840
will have a brilliant day planned.

38:21.840 --> 38:24.800
First, there will be lots of presents to open,

38:24.800 --> 38:27.640
then we'll go somewhere special together.

38:27.640 --> 38:30.320
We'll go to an expensive restaurant for lunch,

38:30.320 --> 38:34.120
and tonight there will be the best party of my life.

38:34.120 --> 38:37.360
When I was Holly, I was only going to go bowling

38:37.360 --> 38:39.880
with mom, dad, and Sarah.

38:39.880 --> 38:45.320
But I don't think Sarah will go now, not after yesterday.

38:45.320 --> 38:49.840
I'm very sorry, says the cook when I go downstairs.

38:49.840 --> 38:52.040
She looks very worried.

38:52.040 --> 38:54.200
Your breakfast isn't ready yet.

38:54.200 --> 38:58.760
It's just that you don't usually get up this early.

38:58.760 --> 39:02.200
She says and hurries back into the kitchen.

39:02.200 --> 39:05.320
When she comes back, she puts my breakfast on the table,

39:05.320 --> 39:08.960
says, happy birthday, Rosie.

39:08.960 --> 39:11.080
And walks away.

39:11.080 --> 39:15.800
Excuse me, I ask before she gets to the kitchen.

39:15.800 --> 39:17.200
Where's Aunt?

39:17.200 --> 39:19.840
I mean, mom and dad.

39:19.840 --> 39:21.560
Don't you remember?

39:21.560 --> 39:24.480
They're away on business until Wednesday.

39:24.480 --> 39:27.600
But they left your presents in the living room.

39:27.600 --> 39:32.280
I'm not hungry, so I get up and go into the living room.

39:32.280 --> 39:35.600
On the table, there are lots of presents.

39:35.600 --> 39:39.440
I open them and there is everything I always wanted.

39:39.440 --> 39:43.240
There's a new laptop computer, a diamond bracelet,

39:43.240 --> 39:45.800
and a new mobile phone.

39:45.800 --> 39:48.400
But there is no one to watch me open them

39:48.400 --> 39:50.800
and to say thank you to.

39:50.800 --> 39:54.600
I can't believe I feel even emptier than before.

39:54.600 --> 39:57.240
Maybe going shopping will help.

39:57.240 --> 40:00.000
I phone Julie first and then Jane.

40:00.000 --> 40:02.320
I ask them if they want to come too.

40:02.320 --> 40:05.360
But they both have something to do or somewhere to go.

40:05.360 --> 40:07.520
So I go by myself.

40:07.520 --> 40:11.040
But it's not the same and I don't buy anything.

40:11.040 --> 40:13.640
Nothing looks nice anymore.

40:13.640 --> 40:16.520
There is nothing I want today.

40:16.520 --> 40:19.120
When mom and I go shopping, we always have a laugh

40:19.120 --> 40:20.640
and an ice cream.

40:20.640 --> 40:23.640
But today nothing has any flavor.

40:23.640 --> 40:26.960
I walk past the bowling alley and from a distance,

40:26.960 --> 40:30.560
I watch as mom and dad have fun with Rosie.

40:30.560 --> 40:34.080
Rosie is now me, Ollie.

40:34.080 --> 40:36.560
Rosie too is smiling and relaxed,

40:36.560 --> 40:39.160
and she looks happier than ever.

40:39.160 --> 40:41.720
Then I see Ben.

40:41.720 --> 40:44.720
Ben, what are you doing here?

40:44.720 --> 40:48.560
I smile, but he doesn't smile back.

40:48.560 --> 40:53.160
When he sees me, his eyes become dark and angry.

40:53.160 --> 40:56.120
You know, I really like Ollie.

40:56.120 --> 40:58.640
I just hope she will understand when I explain

40:58.640 --> 41:02.640
that I didn't know about your stupid trick.

41:02.640 --> 41:08.160
How can you be so horrible to your own cousin, to anyone?

41:08.160 --> 41:13.160
Then he walks on and I am left alone once more.

41:13.160 --> 41:15.640
I want to be me again.

41:15.640 --> 41:18.160
But how can that happen now?

41:18.160 --> 41:20.840
There's nothing I can do.

41:20.840 --> 41:23.080
This is my life now.

41:23.080 --> 41:25.080
Or is it?

41:28.040 --> 41:30.040
Listening activity.

41:32.080 --> 41:34.080
1

41:34.080 --> 41:37.080
1915

41:37.080 --> 41:40.080
2

41:40.080 --> 41:43.080
2000

41:43.080 --> 41:45.080
3

41:45.080 --> 41:50.080
1625

41:50.080 --> 41:52.080
4

41:52.080 --> 41:55.080
1764

41:55.080 --> 41:58.080
5

41:58.080 --> 42:01.080
2012

42:01.080 --> 42:03.080
6

42:03.080 --> 42:06.080
1989

42:06.080 --> 42:09.080
7

42:09.080 --> 42:14.080
24th of February 1997

42:14.080 --> 42:17.080
8

42:17.080 --> 42:26.080
Tuesday 16th of June 2020

42:26.080 --> 42:28.080
Chapter 7

42:28.080 --> 42:32.080
Finding the Old Woman

42:32.080 --> 42:36.080
I love spring, and today is a perfect day of blue sky

42:36.080 --> 42:38.080
and warm sunshine.

42:38.080 --> 42:41.080
But as I go to the fair, I don't notice the weather.

42:41.080 --> 42:43.080
I am too nervous.

42:43.080 --> 42:45.080
Will the old woman be there?

42:45.080 --> 42:48.080
Will she make me holly again?

42:48.080 --> 42:50.080
I have lots of money now.

42:50.080 --> 42:54.080
As Rosie, I can give her all the money she asks for.

42:54.080 --> 42:58.080
I think about being holly again, and I smile and walk faster.

42:58.080 --> 43:05.080
But when I get to the fair, there is no loud music, no bright lights, no rides and no people.

43:05.080 --> 43:09.080
There are only two caravans left.

43:09.080 --> 43:13.080
As I go towards one, I can see a very tall man.

43:13.080 --> 43:18.080
He is connecting one of the caravans to a big lorry and is about to leave.

43:18.080 --> 43:21.080
Excuse me, I ask.

43:21.080 --> 43:23.080
Where's the fair?

43:23.080 --> 43:26.080
It's going back to Russia.

43:26.080 --> 43:29.080
He says in a very loud voice.

43:29.080 --> 43:32.080
He has a Russian accent.

43:32.080 --> 43:33.080
Russia?

43:33.080 --> 43:34.080
But it can't.

43:34.080 --> 43:39.080
I have to see the old woman, the one that makes wishes come true.

43:39.080 --> 43:41.080
But the man doesn't answer.

43:41.080 --> 43:49.080
He gets into the lorry and as he starts the engine.

43:49.080 --> 43:52.080
I say, please, you don't understand.

43:52.080 --> 43:55.080
I'm not really the person you can see.

43:55.080 --> 43:58.080
My wish changed me into my cousin.

43:58.080 --> 44:00.080
But now I want to be me again.

44:00.080 --> 44:04.080
Please, I can't be like this forever.

44:04.080 --> 44:08.080
My eyes fill with tears and I can't help crying.

44:08.080 --> 44:11.080
Only then does he turn to look at me.

44:11.080 --> 44:14.080
For a moment he doesn't say anything.

44:14.080 --> 44:16.080
Please, I say.

44:16.080 --> 44:22.080
The fair stops once more before we go back to Russia.

44:22.080 --> 44:29.080
But in London, if you want to see the old woman, you'll have to go to London.

44:29.080 --> 44:33.080
Tonight, tomorrow morning we all leave.

44:33.080 --> 44:36.080
Then he drives away.

44:36.080 --> 44:40.080
London, I need to get a train now.

44:40.080 --> 44:44.080
Mom and Dad will be so angry with me.

44:44.080 --> 44:50.080
They don't want me to go on trains on my own until I'm 16, in two years.

44:50.080 --> 44:53.080
But I must go now.

44:53.080 --> 44:55.080
I run back home.

44:55.080 --> 44:58.080
When I get back, the house is full of people.

44:58.080 --> 45:01.080
It's my birthday party.

45:01.080 --> 45:03.080
Everyone is there early.

45:03.080 --> 45:08.080
But nobody notices when I go in or when I go back out with a bag.

45:08.080 --> 45:11.080
They're all dancing, eating and laughing.

45:11.080 --> 45:14.080
But I have to get to London.

45:14.080 --> 45:20.080
My dad thinks I'm still a baby and my mum always says that my bedroom is always untidy.

45:20.080 --> 45:23.080
But I miss them so much.

45:23.080 --> 45:26.080
It will take a couple of hours to get to London.

45:26.080 --> 45:30.080
The train is quite empty and there are lots of places to sit.

45:30.080 --> 45:37.080
But because it's my first time on a train by myself, I sit next to a young mother and her crying baby.

45:37.080 --> 45:39.080
This makes me feel safer.

45:39.080 --> 45:44.080
As I put my bag down, the mother smiles and says,

45:44.080 --> 45:47.080
Sorry about Poppy, it's her teeth.

45:47.080 --> 45:49.080
She's only six months old.

45:49.080 --> 45:57.080
That's okay, I try to smile, but when I see the mother and her baby, my eyes feel with tears.

45:57.080 --> 46:01.080
Excuse me, can you look after my bag for a moment?

46:01.080 --> 46:05.080
I ask and I get up and go to the toilet.

46:05.080 --> 46:07.080
I wash my face with cold water.

46:07.080 --> 46:11.080
But when I go back to my seat, my eyes are still red.

46:11.080 --> 46:15.080
I see the mother and her baby getting off the train as I get back.

46:15.080 --> 46:19.080
She waves and smiles at me from the platform.

46:19.080 --> 46:22.080
I sit alone until the train gets to London.

46:22.080 --> 46:27.080
When I finally get off the train, my arms and legs feel heavy and tired.

46:27.080 --> 46:34.080
So I sit down in a cafe to have a coffee and something to eat and think about what to do next.

46:34.080 --> 46:37.080
I eat my sandwich quickly.

46:37.080 --> 46:40.080
I must find the fair and the old woman.

46:40.080 --> 46:44.080
I ask the waitress for the bill and I look for my money.

46:44.080 --> 46:47.080
But my purse is not in my bag.

46:47.080 --> 46:52.080
Listening activity.

46:52.080 --> 46:58.080
Good morning and welcome to Weatherwise 7-Day Forecast.

46:58.080 --> 47:06.080
For those of you hoping for a sunny start to the week, I'm afraid we are expecting heavy rain for Monday.

47:06.080 --> 47:13.080
The weather will get worse and storms are forecast for both Tuesday and Wednesday.

47:14.080 --> 47:17.080
But on Thursday you can leave your umbrella at home.

47:17.080 --> 47:22.080
It will be sunny with temperatures of 25 in the south.

47:22.080 --> 47:28.080
Friday will be cloudy though and on Saturday there will be strong winds.

47:28.080 --> 47:33.080
But then the sun will return for another hot and sunny Sunday.

47:33.080 --> 47:38.080
Chapter 8.

47:38.080 --> 47:43.080
I want to be me.

47:43.080 --> 47:45.080
Please tell me this isn't happening.

47:45.080 --> 47:47.080
My purse was here before.

47:47.080 --> 47:50.080
I know I had it when I got on the train.

47:50.080 --> 47:52.080
Where is it now?

47:52.080 --> 47:54.080
I empty my bag onto the table.

47:54.080 --> 47:58.080
There are my keys, some eyeshadow and a lipstick.

47:58.080 --> 48:01.080
But my purse and mobile phone aren't there.

48:02.080 --> 48:04.080
How can I pay the bill now?

48:04.080 --> 48:09.080
I've only got the small bag with the change from when I bought my train ticket.

48:09.080 --> 48:12.080
I can't even phone anybody to come and help.

48:12.080 --> 48:17.080
I watch the waitress as she takes another order before disappearing inside the cafe

48:17.080 --> 48:20.080
and I know I have to do something wrong.

48:20.080 --> 48:24.080
I look around and check that no one is watching me.

48:24.080 --> 48:26.080
Then I get up and run.

48:26.080 --> 48:29.080
I run as fast as I can.

48:29.080 --> 48:37.080
And when I think I can't run anymore, I think about the police arresting me and I run even faster.

48:37.080 --> 48:41.080
I only stop when I am sure I am about to die.

48:41.080 --> 48:49.080
It is now dark and I am in London, one of the busiest cities in the world, with no money.

48:49.080 --> 48:52.080
Where am I going to sleep tonight?

48:52.080 --> 48:56.080
The maid won't be worried because I told her that I was going to stay with Julie for a few days

48:56.080 --> 49:02.080
and my aunt and uncle are too busy with business meetings and making even more money to worry.

49:02.080 --> 49:05.080
But then I see a poster.

49:05.080 --> 49:07.080
One night only.

49:07.080 --> 49:11.080
The world famous Stavisloski Family Fair.

49:11.080 --> 49:13.080
Covent Garden.

49:13.080 --> 49:16.080
Last stop on European tour.

49:16.080 --> 49:18.080
Don't miss it.

49:18.080 --> 49:25.080
I run as fast as I can to the tube station and with the last of my money I buy a ticket to Covent Garden.

49:26.080 --> 49:29.080
I have to change trains twice to get there.

49:29.080 --> 49:33.080
There is a train in a few minutes so I quickly run to the platform.

49:33.080 --> 49:37.080
But after 15 minutes, the train is still not there.

49:37.080 --> 49:41.080
The train arriving at platform 2 is delayed.

49:41.080 --> 49:43.080
We apologise.

49:43.080 --> 49:46.080
I wait and wait.

49:46.080 --> 49:49.080
And then the train finally arrives.

49:49.080 --> 49:52.080
When I get to the fair, it is late.

49:52.080 --> 49:56.080
There are only a few people left and they are leaving.

49:56.080 --> 50:01.080
I see three girls who look about my age working on one of the rides.

50:01.080 --> 50:03.080
Excuse me, I say.

50:03.080 --> 50:07.080
I'm looking for an elderly lady, I continue.

50:07.080 --> 50:12.080
And when I finish telling them my story, I ask, is she here?

50:12.080 --> 50:13.080
Yes.

50:13.080 --> 50:15.080
Says one of the girls.

50:15.080 --> 50:21.080
She has short dark hair and very big blue eyes that are very difficult not to look at.

50:21.080 --> 50:22.080
She's here.

50:22.080 --> 50:23.080
Excellent.

50:23.080 --> 50:25.080
I smile.

50:25.080 --> 50:27.080
Everything is going to be okay.

50:27.080 --> 50:34.080
But you must know that she is the 8th daughter of the world famous magician, Slavistavislovski.

50:34.080 --> 50:38.080
8th daughters have very special powers.

50:38.080 --> 50:42.080
But once they are used, they cannot go back.

50:42.080 --> 50:45.080
But you don't understand.

50:45.080 --> 50:48.080
I can't be like this forever.

50:49.080 --> 50:53.080
If I can just see her, I'm sure that if I explain everything.

50:53.080 --> 50:58.080
We'll take you to her, but she'll tell you the same thing.

50:58.080 --> 51:02.080
Nervously, I follow them to a caravan.

51:02.080 --> 51:08.080
They go inside and after the longest five minutes of my life, they come out again.

51:08.080 --> 51:09.080
You can go in now.

51:09.080 --> 51:12.080
Says the girl with the blue eyes.

51:12.080 --> 51:17.080
I climb the two steps and when I see her there, I am sure she will help.

51:17.080 --> 51:25.080
I'm so pleased to see you, I say smiling, but she holds her hand up to stop me.

51:25.080 --> 51:30.080
Lord Mila told me why you're here.

51:30.080 --> 51:33.080
I'm sorry, but I can do nothing.

51:33.080 --> 51:40.080
But I asked you if you were sure you wanted things to change.

51:40.080 --> 51:43.080
You said yes.

51:43.080 --> 51:44.080
I know.

51:44.080 --> 51:46.080
I was wrong.

51:46.080 --> 51:47.080
Please.

51:47.080 --> 51:50.080
You have to turn me back into Holly.

51:50.080 --> 51:53.080
I don't have any more money, but...

51:53.080 --> 51:55.080
I know.

51:55.080 --> 52:01.080
The young mother on the train took your money and your phone too.

52:01.080 --> 52:03.080
How do you know that?

52:03.080 --> 52:09.080
I am the 8th daughter of the famous Slavistovski.

52:10.080 --> 52:15.080
When I was 10, my father said to me,

52:15.080 --> 52:21.080
Octavia, you have a special gift,

52:21.080 --> 52:25.080
but you must use that gift carefully.

52:25.080 --> 52:33.080
Everyone has one wish and only one wish.

52:33.080 --> 52:36.080
You had one wish.

52:36.080 --> 52:39.080
You wanted to be Rosie.

52:39.080 --> 52:42.080
I made your wish come true.

52:42.080 --> 52:52.080
I'm sorry, but I cannot help.

52:52.080 --> 52:54.080
Chapter 9.

52:54.080 --> 52:57.080
No more wishes.

52:57.080 --> 53:00.080
But you have to do something.

53:00.080 --> 53:04.080
I can't be Rosie for one more minute.

53:04.080 --> 53:06.080
I want to be Holly.

53:06.080 --> 53:09.080
I want my family back, please.

53:09.080 --> 53:13.080
When I get back, I can get you some more money.

53:13.080 --> 53:18.080
I'm not rich like Rosie, but I do have some money, please.

53:18.080 --> 53:22.080
I can't give you another wish.

53:22.080 --> 53:26.080
But you will be Holly again.

53:26.080 --> 53:30.080
My wishes aren't forever.

53:30.080 --> 53:34.080
You will be Holly again at midnight.

53:34.080 --> 53:39.080
She puts a hand on my shoulder and smiles.

53:39.080 --> 53:43.080
I thank her and I'm about to leave when she says,

53:43.080 --> 53:51.080
In the future, be careful what you wish for.

53:51.080 --> 53:54.080
As the train leaves the station,

53:54.080 --> 53:58.080
I look out of the window at all the lights in people's houses,

53:58.080 --> 54:01.080
bright against the black sky.

54:01.080 --> 54:03.080
I see Rosie's face looking at me,

54:03.080 --> 54:06.080
and for the first time since I became her,

54:06.080 --> 54:08.080
I am happy.

54:08.080 --> 54:12.080
I try to keep my eyes open, but I'm very tired,

54:12.080 --> 54:16.080
and as I sit back in my seat, my eyes start to close.

54:16.080 --> 54:18.080
I fight sleep.

54:18.080 --> 54:20.080
I must stay awake.

54:20.080 --> 54:21.080
I must.

54:21.080 --> 54:25.080
But eventually sleep wins.

54:25.080 --> 54:28.080
I dream of my bedroom, the posters on the wall,

54:28.080 --> 54:33.080
the mess and mum shouting that I must tidy up in the morning.

54:33.080 --> 54:38.080
I dream of my favourite things like watching DVDs on rainy Sunday afternoons,

54:38.080 --> 54:44.080
chocolate ice cream and getting into a clean bed after having a long relaxing bath.

54:44.080 --> 54:47.080
Holly, breakfast's ready.

54:47.080 --> 54:51.080
Someone shouts, and at first I think I'm still sleeping.

54:51.080 --> 54:53.080
But then I hear it again.

54:53.080 --> 54:55.080
It sounds like mum.

54:55.080 --> 54:57.080
My mum.

54:57.080 --> 55:00.080
I open my eyes, but I'm not on the train.

55:00.080 --> 55:01.080
I'm home.

55:01.080 --> 55:03.080
In my bed.

55:03.080 --> 55:06.080
I throw the duvet off and run down the stairs.

55:06.080 --> 55:10.080
But when I pass the mirror in the hall, I stop suddenly.

55:10.080 --> 55:12.080
I have to see.

55:12.080 --> 55:17.080
But opening my eyes to check that I'm not Rosie anymore is very hard.

55:17.080 --> 55:20.080
Please let me look like a clown.

55:20.080 --> 55:23.080
Slowly I open my eyes.

55:23.080 --> 55:24.080
Yes!

55:24.080 --> 55:28.080
I shout so loud that mum comes out of the kitchen.

55:28.080 --> 55:31.080
Holly, what's the matter?

55:31.080 --> 55:32.080
Nothing mum.

55:32.080 --> 55:34.080
Everything's perfect.

55:34.080 --> 55:37.080
I say giving her a big kiss.

55:37.080 --> 55:38.080
Good.

55:38.080 --> 55:41.080
Now come and get your breakfast before it goes cold.

55:41.080 --> 55:44.080
Mum is surprised and laughs.

55:44.080 --> 55:48.080
There is a knock on the front door.

55:48.080 --> 55:51.080
Please can you open the door, Holly?

55:51.080 --> 55:55.080
Shouts mum before going back into the kitchen.

55:55.080 --> 55:59.080
Is it the postman or the milkman coming for his money?

55:59.080 --> 56:03.080
But it's Rosie, and she looks very sad.

56:03.080 --> 56:06.080
For a moment we just look at each other.

56:06.080 --> 56:08.080
Do you want to go for a walk?

56:08.080 --> 56:11.080
She says, I think we need to talk.

56:11.080 --> 56:15.080
We walk for a while, and then I say,

56:15.080 --> 56:18.080
I'm not looking forward to going to school tomorrow.

56:18.080 --> 56:21.080
Not after the basketball match.

56:21.080 --> 56:23.080
And I must speak to Sarah.

56:23.080 --> 56:25.080
Don't worry Holly.

56:25.080 --> 56:27.080
Sarah will understand.

56:27.080 --> 56:32.080
And as for everyone else, no one will say anything to you.

56:32.080 --> 56:34.080
Rosie says with a smile.

56:34.080 --> 56:39.080
I'll make sure that no one is horrible to you ever again.

56:39.080 --> 56:42.080
I'm so sorry for what I did to you.

56:42.080 --> 56:45.080
You know, Ben really likes you.

56:45.080 --> 56:48.080
You should go and see him.

56:48.080 --> 56:50.080
That's okay Rosie.

56:50.080 --> 56:54.080
Let's forget about it, and be friends as well as cousins.

56:54.080 --> 56:59.080
I say smiling at my cousin.

56:59.080 --> 57:05.080
As Holly and Rosie walk out of the front door,

57:05.080 --> 57:09.080
Holly's mum starts going upstairs.

57:10.080 --> 57:13.080
She sees something on the floor.

57:13.080 --> 57:17.080
She picks it up.

57:17.080 --> 57:19.080
A train ticket to London.

57:19.080 --> 57:22.080
Where did that come from?

57:22.080 --> 57:30.080
She puts it in her pocket and continues with her day.

57:30.080 --> 57:35.080
The only person I know who goes to London is my sister Lily.

57:35.080 --> 57:42.080
She says to herself later as she is cleaning the bathroom.

57:42.080 --> 57:45.080
I wish I were rich like Lily,

57:45.080 --> 57:49.080
so that I could go shopping all day and not have to do housework.

57:49.080 --> 57:55.080
Just for one day, I'd like to be Lily.

57:55.080 --> 58:04.080
She says, and then suddenly something strange happens.

